# Bench baseline. Refresh whenever optimise/import internals change
# (rerun the exact commands below, replace numbers, note the machine).
# Regressions are judged against this file, not against memory.

machine: i5-14600KF (20 threads), ext4, linux 7.1.3-arch1-3
date: 2026-07-17

## bench/run.sh 400 2000 5000 1   (800k files, 194 MiB dedupable)

populate (addToStore)    17.120 s
optimise pass1 (cold)     8.929 s   linked 794600 files
optimise pass2 (warm)     0.014 s   linked 0

History: serial optimiseStore (pre thread-pool, same params, same
machine) cold pass was ~9-12 s; the parallel win on this box is
bounded by link-farm creation, not scanning. Commit 01ad51c holds the
original 1000x1000x100k serial capture: populate 14.1 s, cold 23.0 s.

## build/bench-import <root> 20000 32 10000   (640 MiB tree, 43% dup)

import (capture off)     0.487 s
optimise (capture off)   0.568 s   linked 11366
import (capture on)      0.577 s   linked 11366
optimise (capture on)    0.213 s

Capture trades ~0.09 s at import (second hash thread) for ~2.7x
faster optimise (no content re-read); linked counts must match
on/off, a divergence means the captured hashes drifted (see
tests/import-hashes.cc).

## bench/run-real.sh   (arch-base: 582 MiB, 33k entries, NVMe ext4)

capture off/on (cold farm)  import 0.917 / 0.921 s
                            optimise 0.556 / 0.247 s   linked 9731
fresh install (import-dir)  wall 1.5 s
update, 1-file variant      wall 1.3 s   linked 31704, freed 545.6 MiB

The update phase is the on-box nixgen-update/commit hot path. Cost
per duplicate file is two journaled metadata writes (farm hardlink +
atomic rename); NVMe does ~10 us/op, USB-class flash ~1-2 ms/op, so
the same 33k-file generation that optimises in 0.3 s here takes tens
of seconds on a stick. That is media, not code: to measure a box,
run with the work dir on the target medium:
  bench/run-real.sh <tree> /path/on/that/medium

